<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-325-310  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 325 310.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 2 1990 v9 n7 p34(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army might modify CALS contract to add systems. (theComputer-Aided Acquisition and Logistics Support system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Karen D.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government ContractsMilitaryDefense ContractsPlanningEquipment AcquisitionLogisticsCompetitive BiddingSystem DesignUnited States. Army.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Army Might Modify CALS Contract to Add SystemsandM;The Army is considering modifying its $400 million Computer-Aided Acquisitionand Logistics Support system contract to include more systems.andM;The modifications would add several systems to the contract.andP;  Those systemshave not yet been determined, said Bob Wallace, Army CALS project manager atComputer Sciences Corp., one of three contractors.andM;Helen Garamone, an Army spokeswoman, said officials are considering themodification and they have not reached a decision.andP;  She said if the contractwere modified, it would encompass several &quot;islands of automation.&quot;andM;The Army Information Systems Selection and Acquisition Agency last Augustawarded the first phase of the service's CALS effort to BDM InternationalInc., Xerox Corp., Computer Sciences Corp. and TRW Inc.andM;The contractors are competing over 13 months to develop a systemarchitecture.andP;  They will design interface software to bridge gaps betweenwidely varying hardware, software and communications.andM;The awards total $15.8 million.andM;The Army also planned last month to complete compiling data from 56 sitesurveys and distributing the results to the four contractors.andM;The companies will use the information to design a system that will handlethe sites' general automation needs.andP;  The system also should be flexibleenough to satisfy each site's requirements.andM;The Army assigned 14 sites to each contractor.andP;  The contractors gathered dataon the type of hardware and local area networks used at the sites andreported the results back to the Army.andM;Although the contractors are not limited as to the software, hardware andcommunications equipment they can propose, Garamone said the contractorsshould try to make the maximum use of the Defense Data Network andtelecommunications media.andM;They should give priority to Ada-compatible off-the-shelf products and useoff-the-shelf software and hardware components, she said.andM;The Army will choose up to two of the four contractors in September to moveon to the 10-month concept demonstration phase.andO;</TEXT></DOC>